  "doc_id": "22176",
  "text": "is is especially of concern since corneal sensitivity correlates with blinking frequency [CITATION_1] and hence with lubrication of the eye, aiding in an uncomplicated recovery. On the other hand, corneal debridement can be a cause of multiple complications, such as corneal infiltrates, subepithelial haze, ulcers, and scarring [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . e irrigation time with riboflavin was chosen to be 10 minutes, reduced in comparison to the Dresden protocol (30 minutes [CITATION_4] ), since irrigation happened beneath the flap and increased in comparison to the IntraLase-pocket CXL (2 minutes [CITATION_5] ), since riboflavin was washed out subsequently. Identifying the required time of riboflavin irrigation for an effective corneal stabilization in our treatment, however, stays a pivotal question. In addition to a longer follow-up, we suggest to determine the stromal demarcation line one month after treatment. e demarcation line possibly indicates the separation between treated and untreated cornea [CITATION_6] . It appears as early as 2 weeks following CXL at an approximate depth of 300 micrometers and can be visualized at the slitlamp and with anterior segment OCT [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
